00:00:12.000 --> 00:00:15.000
and now let's look at how to compute this.

00:00:15.000 --> 00:00:17.000
We have to take two different forces into account.

00:00:17.000 --> 00:00:21.000
The force due to friction, biking that is, and the force due to gravity.

00:00:21.000 --> 00:00:25.000
Newton says F=m&lt;i&gt;a.&lt;/i&gt;

00:00:25.000 --> 00:00:29.000
The force due to friction equals the mass of the car

00:00:29.000 --> 00:00:33.000
times the deceleration as we are breaking off the car.

00:00:33.000 --> 00:00:38.000
But the force exerted due to friction is amountable of the force exerted by gravity

00:00:38.000 --> 00:00:44.000
with the proportionality constant µ and what's force the exerted by gravity?

00:00:44.000 --> 00:00:47.000
It's the mass of the car times the gravitational acceleration of the earth.

00:00:47.000 --> 00:00:50.000
You see that's Newton law applied in the reverse direction.

00:00:50.000 --> 00:00:55.000
If you look closely, you'll see that mass cancels from both sides of the equation

00:00:55.000 --> 00:01:00.000
and the deceleration equals the constant of friction times the gravitation acceleration.

00:01:00.000 --> 00:01:03.000
This is one funny consequence for astronauts.

00:01:03.000 --> 00:01:09.000
When you try to break a car on the moon, the gravitational acceleration is far less than on earth

00:01:09.000 --> 00:01:11.000
and so the deceleration is far less than on earth.

00:01:11.000 --> 00:01:16.000
Breaking is far more ineffective on the moon than on earth.

00:01:16.000 --> 00:01:19.000
